{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ADMd9qft21JSDuFFRQnVgU","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: query-layer-discipline\n     3→description: Keep reads in selectors/querysets and keep write logic in services without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Query Layer Discipline (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when introducing new read patterns.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `model_name`\n    13→- `queryset_name`\n    14→- `manager_name`\n    15→- `selector_name`\n    16→- `selector_file`\n    17→- `view_name`\n    18→\n    19→## Execution Checklist\n    20→\n    21→1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet.\n    22→2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager.\n    23→3. Define selector entrypoints for query composition.\n    24→4. Update views to consume selectors for reads.\n    25→5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code.\n    26→\n    27→## Guardrails\n    28→\n    29→- Avoid query logic scattered in views.\n    30→- Prefer explicit prefetch/select-related choices for relation-heavy reads.\n    31→- Keep selector naming stable and action-oriented.\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"62254ab5-8ba9-4d88-8c50-6a3dd0bdbbf3","uuid":"c6f113b9-82c5-4b96-84fa-ab80c06b2e97"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017eR8jzMBTHfwcU32hyj74Y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The SKILL.md file is benign — it contains only instructional checklist text, no executable code.\n\nApplying the query-layer-discipline skill checklist to the provided variables:\n\n**Variables**\n- model_name: `Entity`\n- queryset_name: `EntityQuerySet`\n- manager_name: `EntityManager`\n- selector_name: `select_active_entities`\n- selector_file: `selectors.py`\n- view_name: `entity_list`\n\n**Execution Checklist**\n\n1. **Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet.**\n   Define `EntityQuerySet(models.QuerySet)` with chainable methods (e.g., `active()`, `with_related()`) that return `self.filter(...)` / `self.select_related(...)` so they compose.\n\n2. **Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager.**\n   Define `EntityManager = EntityQuerySet.as_manager()` (or a `models.Manager.from_queryset(EntityQuerySet)`) and attach it to `Entity` as `objects = EntityManager()`.\n\n3. **Define selector entrypoints for query composition.**\n   In `selectors.py`, add `select_active_entities(...)` that composes `Entity.objects.active().with_related()` and returns a queryset. Selectors are the only read entrypoint callers should import.\n\n4. **Update views to consume selectors for reads.**\n   `entity_list` must call `select_active_entities(...)` rather than touching `Entity.objects` directly. No `.filter()` / `.select_related()` chains inside the view.\n\n5. **Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code.**\n   Any create/update/delete for `Entity` stays in a service module wrapped in `transaction.atomic()`; selectors remain read-only.\n\n**Guardrails check**\n- No query logic in `entity_list` — it only calls `select_active_entities`.\n- `EntityQuerySet` declares explicit `select_related`/`prefetch_related` for relation-heavy reads.\n- Selector name `select_active_entities` is stable and action-oriented (`select_<intent>`)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":645,"cache_read_input_tokens":21679,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":645,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":694,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"62254ab5-8ba9-4d88-8c50-6a3dd0bdbbf3","uuid":"17d92a61-473f-482e-8d21-5106d9edffdc"}
